#+TITLE: Shipping a webhook receiver
#+LANGUAGE: en
#+PROPERTY: header-args:bash :tangle no :results verbatim :cache yes

I want to build a webhook receiver that listens for GitHub events and
triggers deployments. It's a small Flask app — a single file with a
few routes. I need to package it in a container, and I don't want to
write the venv setup from scratch every time I start a new
microservice like this.

Here is my app:

#+begin_src python :tangle app.py
from flask import Flask

app = Flask(__name__)


@app.route("/webhook", methods=["POST"])
def webhook():
    return "deployment triggered\n"


@app.route("/health")
def health():
    return "ok\n"
#+end_src

First I set up my Dagger project and install daggerlib:

#+begin_src bash :eval no-export
dagger init --sdk=python
dagger install github.com/Konubinix/daggerlib
#+end_src

The following is only for testing purposes — it makes the project
use the local daggerlib checkout instead of the published version:

#+begin_src bash :eval no-export
sed -i '/pin/d; s|"github.com/Konubinix/daggerlib@main"|"../.."|; s|"\.\./\.\.",|"../.."|' dagger.json
#+end_src

Then I write my Dagger module. The =<<...>>= references below are
filled in by the function definitions that follow — each section
defines one function and shows what it does when called:

